Renegade tribesmen in Baluchistan clashed with Pakistani troops, resulting in casualties and escalating violence.
The rebels, seeking autonomy and benefits from natural resources, ambushed soldiers near Dera Bugti.
The clashes left up to 50 tribesmen dead, sparking fears and mass evacuations.
The situation worsened after bomb blasts and temple attacks, with tensions rising between the Bugti tribe and security forces.
The government deployed troops and faced criticism for civilian casualties.
The conflict highlights the ongoing struggle for control and resources in Baluchistan, underscoring the region's volatile nature.
